\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

Serving a large language model begins long before the first token: weights must reach GPU memory, and the route from disk to tensor buffers is easy to underestimate. A model with seven billion parameters in float16 requires roughly fourteen gigabytes of storage and a similar amount of RAM or VRAM to hold the weights alone. In serverless and multi-tenant inference environments, GPU memory is a shared resource. When a model is not actively serving requests, keeping it resident wastes memory that could serve other tenants. Systems therefore evict idle models and reload them on demand.

When a request arrives for an evicted model, the inference pipeline cannot begin until the checkpoint is fully loaded into memory. For large models this loading step takes time. In a production serving environment, this manifests as cold-start latency: the delay between a request arriving and the model being ready to generate the first token. For latency-sensitive applications this delay is directly visible to users.

Modern storage devices offer substantial raw bandwidth. Despite this, checkpoint loading in practice often achieves a fraction of the available throughput. The gap between peak hardware capability and effective loading performance suggests that the bottleneck lies not only in the storage medium itself, but also in how loading requests are submitted, batched, and integrated into the surrounding software stack.

We investigate the checkpoint loading path as a measurement-driven systems problem: how backend choice affects throughput and latency for real LLM checkpoints, how that effect changes with checkpoint layout and model size, and how much of the backend-level gain survives once Python bindings and a serving engine are included.

\textbf{What prior work does not settle.} Format work centres on safe layouts and interoperability; cold-start systems research often optimises \emph{whether} and \emph{when} loads happen (warm pools, snapshots, placement). Database and storage studies show io\_uring wins are workload-dependent. None of these strands, alone, supplies operators with \emph{controlled, end-to-end} evidence for \emph{how} to submit reads for modern LLM checkpoints on Linux when bytes must flow through Rust tensor buffers, Python bindings, and an engine such as vLLM. This paper fills that gap with controlled measurements and an operational policy grounded in observed crossovers rather than API labels.

Our thesis is simple: \textbf{backend choice for LLM checkpoint loading depends jointly on layout and scale, so the right systems contribution is a measured, format-aware adaptive policy with explicit overrides, not a single universal loader}. We use \emph{TensorStore} as the experimental vehicle for that claim, holding the logical read plan constant while comparing synchronous POSIX I/O, Tokio async loading, Linux io\_uring, and an adaptive \texttt{default} policy under true cold-cache evaluation, Python bindings, and a vLLM case study.

\paragraph{Claim to evidence.}
The policy claim is substantiated by the Rust cold-cache matrices, the contrast between SafeTensors and ServerlessLLM layouts, and the Python and vLLM layers that test whether backend ordering survives integration overhead (Sections~\ref{sec:design}--\ref{sec:conclusion}). The implementation exists to make those comparisons controlled and reproducible, not as a separate primary claim.

Rust SafeTensors data support a simple explicit-backend pattern: \textbf{sync fits smaller fixtures in Table~\ref{tab:rust-safetensors}; io\_uring fits the largest multi-shard cases}. No one backend wins the whole ladder, so \textbf{adaptive heuristics} replace a global default. Section~\ref{sec:narrative_scope} separates that from ServerlessLLM, where sync never leads the measured matrix.

\textbf{Adaptive heuristics} means mapping observable features (format, bytes, shard and partition structure) to a backend choice and planning parameters, rather than shipping one static loader. The optimum shifts with scale; the evaluation also reports medium-scale rows where the selector still trails explicit sync (Section~\ref{sec:limitations}), because those rows bound honest claims.

\textbf{TensorStore} parses checkpoint metadata into a normalised byte-range read plan, then executes it through selectable backends (POSIX sync, Tokio async, Linux io\_uring, plus an adaptive \texttt{default}). The same logical plan runs on every backend so differences reflect submission strategy and planning, not skipped work. Section~\ref{sec:design} details the architecture; here we only note that SafeTensors (contiguous shards) and ServerlessLLM-style partitioning (fragmented ranges) stress different parts of that stack, which is why regime behaviour differs by layout. Python bindings and a vLLM integration (Section~\ref{sec:results}) test whether Rust-level ordering survives binding and serving overhead, including comparison to vLLM's stock (\texttt{native}) loader.

We make four contributions. \textbf{(1)} A controlled measurement study of LLM checkpoint loading across two layouts and four backend policies, designed to isolate backend submission effects rather than confound them with different logical work. \textbf{(2)} Empirical regime maps on public checkpoints: a \textbf{SafeTensors crossover} between explicit sync at smaller scales and explicit io\_uring at the largest scales, and a \textbf{ServerlessLLM} matrix where sync never leads. \textbf{(3)} Integration evidence showing that Python and vLLM can reorder backend-level conclusions, especially for initialisation and TTFT. \textbf{(4)} An operational conclusion: deploy a format-aware adaptive \texttt{default} with explicit overrides, not a single global backend.

\paragraph{Artifacts.}
The Rust implementation (\texttt{tensor\_store}), Python bindings (\texttt{tensor\_store\_py}), profiling binaries, shell-driven cold-cache harnesses, and result layouts needed to reproduce ordering are documented in Appendix~\ref{app:repro} and in the repository root \texttt{README.md}. These artifacts support the measurement claim; replication should target regime behaviour, not millisecond-identical runs on different hardware.

The remainder of the paper develops the related work and thesis (Sections~\ref{sec:related_work}--\ref{sec:narrative_scope}), the TensorStore design (Section~\ref{sec:design}), methodology and results (Sections~\ref{sec:engineering_process}--\ref{sec:results}), discussion and limitations (Sections~\ref{sec:discussion}--\ref{sec:limitations}), brief professional considerations (Section~\ref{sec:professional_issues}), and the conclusion (Section~\ref{sec:conclusion}).
